LAST UPDATES

Prof. Dr. Sven Nyholm to join LMU from Utrecht

Sven Nyholm, currently an associate professor of philosophy at Utrecht University, will become the new Professor of Ethics of Artificial Intelligence at the Faculty of Philosophy in LMU Munich. With extensive experience in applied ethics, ethical theory, and the history of ethics, Professor Nyholm has published numerous works in these areas. His appointment is effective from this summer.

Read more here

Playing with the source of world literature

The Electronic Babylonian Literature under Prof. Dr. Enrique Jiménez has used AI to make ancient texts readable. This includes the Gilgamesh epic, which poses the question of how we can live knowing we must die. Scholars have managed to decode two-thirds of this 4,000-year-old text, which survived only as fragments. The writing system is complicated, and the texts were originally written in Sumerian and Akkadian. Jiménez's online platform is now accessible to the public.

AI+MUNICH Prototype Funding

AI+Munich's Prototype Funding program is open for applications from February 27, providing support for talented AI startups in Bavaria. Their goal is to make prototyping more accessible and affordable for teams that haven't yet received financial backing. The program provides funding of up to €25k, which can be used exclusively for developing the business idea, such as specialist scholarships, expert consultations and pools, or prototype funding. The program is open to early-phase and late-phase teams, and it's advantageous if the teams are diverse and have previously won prizes in AI-related competitions. If you meet these criteria, you should consider applying for this opportunity.

Read more here

AI.BAY 2023

The international AI.BAY conference was recently held in Munich, showcasing the state of Bavaria's influence as a world-class location for AI. The two-day event featured high-profile speakers from the global AI community, including representatives from MIT, the University of Amsterdam, and Imperial College London. Over 500 attendees were present in person, and more than 1,500 joined via livestream. Among the keynote speakers were Dr. Markus Söder, Minister of Science and Art Markus Blume, Minister of Digital Affairs Judith Gerlach, and Minister of Economic Affairs Hubert Aiwanger. During the conference, the ministers emphasized the importance of establishing European AI. They also highlighted the state's efforts to become a leader in AI research and development, including the creation of over 100 AI Chairs as part of the Hightech Agenda Bayern, an initiative that has already filled three-quarters of the newly created positions.

Munich AI Lecture with Prof. Dr. René Vidal

The Munich AI Lectures series continues with a talk by Prof. Dr. René Vidal, Professor of  Biomedical Engineering and Director of the Mathematical Institute for Data Science at Johns Hopkins University. On March 8, 5pm, he will give a talk titled "Explainable AI via Semantic Information Pursuit". The talk will be live-streamed online.

Epistemology and Theory of Machine Learning

The upcoming workshop, "Formal Epistemology and the Foundations of Machine Learning" on March 23 and 24  will explore important philosophical questions surrounding the justification, limitations, and interpretability of machine learning methods. The aim of the workshop is to approach these issues from a formal epistemology perspective, drawing from the fields of philosophy, computer science, and mathematics. This workshop concludes the German Research Foundation-funded project, "The Epistemology of Statistical Learning Theory."
